2003-12-24  Martin Bravenboer <martin@cs.uu.nl>

	* spec/posix-file.str: added chdir to change the current working
	directory. Note that chdir implements the error reporting in the
	SSL itself now we have a perror in the SSL. If you really want no
	warning, then you can use the plain primitive.

	This kind of error-reporting is very easy to implement in
	Stratego:

	?pathname; prim("SSL_chdir", pathname) => 0
	<+ < conc-strings
	   ; perror
	   ; fail
	   > ("SSL/chdir: Cannot change current working directory to ", <id>)

	This will for example output the following message if the pathname
	does not exist:
	
        SSL/chdir: Cannot change current working directory to /tddmp: No
	such file or directory

	* tests/posix-file-test.str: tests for chdir

	* Adding new primitives is quite complex now we have separation
	compilation with SSL libraries in the SRTS ...

2003-12-21  Martin Bravenboer <martin@cs.uu.nl>

	* spec/posix-process.str: added execv.

	Note that the implementation in the runtime does not add the
	program to the list of argument. execvp does this, which is
	horrible. I think this should be changed in the runtime part of
	execvp and the invocations to execvp should be adapated.
	
2003-12-19  Eelco Visser  <visser@cs.uu.nl>

	* Improvements for separate compilation
	  - added more modules to lib; since liblib should be
	    the default module to be imported in programs, there
	    should be not need to import other modules that partly
	    overlap. Added annotation-props, sunit. Also added
	    constructor declarations for tuples to library instead
	    of in compiler. 
	  - (In the future it might be interesting to split the
	     library into smaller parts.)
	  - uncify reverses the cification of function names 

	* liblib is a library derived from lib.str. The compiler generates
	liblib.c from which an object library is produced, liblib.str,
	a Stratego module with external definitions for all the definitions
	in lib, and liblib.rtree. Instead of importing lib or some sub-modules
	in a program, one should now (when desired) import liblib. In addition
	it is then necessary to link against the object library. When using
	Makefile.xt this can be done as follows (for a program file.str):

	   file_LDADD = -lliblib $(STRATEGORUNLIBS)

